  "note": "ARCH-11 shared golden vectors for the MCP-server-entry drift guard. Both @ax/sandbox-protocol's McpServerSchema (the host contract) and @ax/agent-claude-sdk-runner's hand-rolled validateMcpEntry (sandbox-side defense-in-depth, intentionally NOT importing the schema) are asserted against THIS one file. Each vector declares its expected verdict PER SIDE: `schema` (McpServerSchema.safeParse(.value).success) and `runner` (validateMcpEntry(.value) returns vs throws). `core: true` vectors test the security-critical shape rules that MUST NEVER diverge — both sides assert schema === runner for those. `core: false` vectors encode the two KNOWN, intentional asymmetries (documented on validateMcpEntry): (a) the runner ignores allowedHosts/credentials, and (b) the runner additionally caps env to <=32 entries and <=256-char keys/values while McpServerSchema's z.record(z.string(),z.string()) caps neither — so the runner (the last gate) is a strict-superset REJECTER, the safe direction. If either validator flips a verdict on any vector, one of the two drift suites fails -> CI red, forcing a conscious fixture + cross-reference update. Note: every vector includes allowedHosts/credentials so McpServerSchema sees them explicitly; the runner ignores them either way.",
